            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe\u2019s eight, sitting on the Mission apartment stoop. His father comes home, smelling of sawdust, and sits beside him. He holds out his hands\u2014calloused, scarred, but powerful. \"Con estas,\" he says softly, \"we build.\" Marco traces a deep line on his father\u2019s palm, feeling the grit and the strength. It wasn't just about wood and nails; it was a lesson in building a life with integrity. That feeling of respectful awe for honest work never left him.\n\n2.\nThe thin envelope from SF State arrived on a Tuesday. He opened it in the kitchen, his mother watching, wiping her hands on her apron. He read the word \"Congratulations\" and looked up. His mother didn't scream; she just brought a hand to her mouth, her eyes welling with tears. When his father saw it that night, he simply nodded, a slow, proud smile spreading across his face. Marco felt the profound weight and honor of being their dream realized.\n\n3.\nHe was in his late twenties, escaping a stressful work week at the Japanese Tea Garden. The fog was thick, muting the world. He saw her sketching the moon bridge in a small notebook. She was a teacher, Elena. They talked for an hour, the damp air making their conversation feel intimate and private. Leaving the park, Marco felt a profound quietness settle in his chest. He knew, with an unshakeable certainty, that his life was no longer just his own.\n\n4.\nThe first morning he had the keys to the downtown store, he stood alone on the sales floor before the lights were fully on. The silence was immense. He thought of his first days stocking shelves in a place just like it, feeling invisible. A wave of quiet panic was quickly replaced by a steady calm. He wasn't the loudest voice in the room, but he knew the work. He had earned this silence, and for the first time, he fully believed he knew how to fill it.\n\n5.\nWeeks after his father\u2019s funeral, Marco was on the N-Judah, watching the fog-laced houses of the Inner Sunset slide by. A history podcast played in his ears, but he wasn\u2019t listening. He saw his father\u2019s hands, his wife\u2019s smile, his own reflection in the window. The relentless drive to manage one more store, to hit one more target, suddenly felt hollow. He imagined a small bookstore, the smell of coffee and paper, and Elena by his side. The ambition hadn't vanished; it had simply changed its address."
